  Group27Deal11: `
  ### The Bidding

South opens the bidding with one spade, choosing his higher suit for the opening bid. North's raise to three spades promises strong trump support of at least four cards, with 13 to 16 points in high cards and distribution. In this case North has 13 points in high cards and 3 points for the singleton. However, he should deduct a point or so rather than count the singleton king of hearts both as a singleton and as a king. South can afford to try for a slam after North's jump raise because he has considerably more than a minimum opening bid. South is willing to play the hand at slam if North has two aces; otherwise not. For this reason South bids 4 NT, the Blackwood Convention. North responds five hearts, showing two aces, and South carries on by jumping to six spades.

  ### The Play

West takes the ace of hearts and gets out with a trump, leaving South to solve his own problems in clubs and diamonds. South draws three rounds of trumps, ending in dummy with the nine of spades and tries the club finesse. Fortunately, this succeeds. Now South's only problem is to play the diamonds to lose no tricks. As in Hand No. 9, South must count the hands of the defenders to see whether either of them is likely to have all four of the missing diamonds. East's discards on the second and third spade indicate strongly that East started with only four or five hearts at most. Since West has followed suit to two rounds of clubs, East started with only five clubs at most. South also knows that East started with exactly one spade. If East has at most six black cards, he must have at least seven red cards. If only five of those can be hearts, East must have at least two diamonds. South must therefore take out insurance against finding all of the diamonds in the East hand. He leads the first diamond to dummy's ace, and West's heart discard confirms his suspicion. On the diamond return from dummy East puts in the nine, and South wins with the queen. Declarer returns to dummy with a trump to lead another diamond through East, and the rest is easy. === PAGE 9 ===
  `,
  Group27Deal12: `
  ### The Bidding

The South hand is not quite worth an opening bid of two hearts. For an opening forcing bid a player should have more quick tricks than losers. In this case, South has two sure losers in diamonds, a possible loser in spades, a possible loser in clubs, and two possible losers in hearts. Even if South optimistically assumes that one of his possible losers will disappear in the wash, he is still left with five losers and only 4½ quick tricks. The North hand would be worth a jump to three hearts even if North were not a passed hand. He has strong 4-card heart support with 12 points in high cards and 1 point for the doubleton. After the jump raise, South counts his 20 points in high cards (and sees that the combined count in high cards alone should be very close to 33 points). Since South also has distributional points and expects to find a distributional point or two in the dummy, he sees that there should be an excellent play for a small slam. South also sees that a grand slam is virtually out of the question. It is most unlikely that North would pass originally with four hearts to the ace, both black kings, and either the doubleton king of diamonds or both the king and queen of diamonds. Since South wants to be in a small slam but not in a grand slam he jumps at once to six hearts, ending the auction.

  ### The Play

At the outset South sees that he has possible finesses in all suits but trumps. If South plans simply to take all three finesses, he will need success in two out of three. His chance is a flat 50%. This is not bad, but South can get a better chance. After drawing trumps, South should take the club finesse. If this should win, South would try for three diamond tricks by taking the king and ace and then leading toward dummy's jack. If that failed, he could still fall back on the spade finesse. Actually, the club finesse fails, but South can get a discard on dummy's jack of clubs. The best discard is a diamond, since that allows him to take the top diamonds and ruff a diamond in the hope of dropping the queen. This chance alone is somewhat better than 50%; and if it failed South would still be in position to try the spade finesse. (If South tried the spade finesse first, he would be down at once if it failed.) Actually, the queen of diamonds does drop, and South needs no further finesse. The play is an exercise in selecting the right order in which to play the suits. The plan is to have a chance in all three suits rather than rely on only two out of the three suits.
  `,
  Group27Deal13: `
  ### The Bidding

South would not be sure of a slam if North had jumped to three spades after a pass by West. North might have heart strength which would not do much to solve all of South's problems in clubs and diamonds. === PAGE 10 === After West's overcall, however, South has reason to believe that West has most or all of the missing heart strength. North's strength must therefore be in the other suits, where it will reinforce South's strength. South uses this knowledge to jump to the slam. If South did not rely on his reading of the bidding he would almost surely miss the slam.

  ### The Play

South notes that he will make his slam if he can succeed in a finesse in either clubs or diamonds, but he should not be optimistic about these finesses. There are only 12 high-card points missing from the North-South hands, and it is quite likely that West has all of them for his vulnerable overcall. After drawing trumps South tries, instead, to develop three club tricks without the usual type of finesse. Instead, he takes the ace and king of clubs, with the intention of leading a club toward the jack if the queen of clubs has not yet dropped. This plan will develop a third club if the suit breaks 3-3; if the queen falls singleton or doubleton; or if East has the queen of clubs no matter how the suit breaks. It is important to note that South does not need the ordinary finesse if East has four or five clubs headed by the queen. East can then take the third club trick, but South will get the fourth club with his jack and can discard dummy's losing diamond on the jack of clubs. It is important to note also that South would lose his slam if he took the king of clubs and then tried a finesse with the jack. This would lose to the queen, and the suit would not break favorably, so that South would be forced to try the diamond finesse later losing to West's king. When the queen of clubs drops on South's actual line of play, South can afford to try the diamond finesse in the attempt to make an overtrick. The finesse loses, but his slam is safe.
  `,
